{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17530274","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17530274"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:04:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:04:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14504"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14504"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.16,0.04,0.72,0.05,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7199"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56369"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7199","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7199"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14504"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41917"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"987"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17425"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17426"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41761"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56369","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/56369"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman presents to her GP with fatigue and tingling in her hands and feet for the last several months. These symptoms have progressively worsened with time. The patient reports no medical history but did undergo gastric bypass surgery two years ago for weight loss management. She has never smoked, drinks two standard drinks per week, and eats a vegetarian diet.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely to be revealed by the blood tests or blood smear for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Microcytic anaemia","Normocytic anaemia","Hyper-segmented neutrophils","Heinz bodies","Elliptocytes"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms and a history suggestive of vitamin B12 deficiency, based on the symptoms of progressive tingling in the hands and feet, and major risk for malabsorption after the gastric bypass surgery. Vitamin B12 deficiency is a common cause of macrocytic anaemia, characterised by the presence of large red blood cells and specific changes in the white blood cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyper-segmented neutrophils\u003C/strong\u003E are a classic finding in vitamin B12 deficiency. These are neutrophils with more than five lobes in their nuclei, and their presence is a hallmark of megaloblastic anaemia, which is often due to vitamin B12 or folate deficiency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMicrocytic anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is typically associated with iron deficiency or thalassaemia, not vitamin B12 deficiency. In microcytic anaemia, red blood cells are smaller than normal, which is not the case here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormocytic anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E refers to anaemia where the red blood cells are of normal size, which can occur in chronic disease or acute blood loss. This is not typical of vitamin B12 deficiency, which causes macrocytic anaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHeinz bodies\u003C/strong\u003E are inclusions within red blood cells that are seen in conditions like G6PD deficiency or oxidative stress, not in vitamin B12 deficiency.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EElliptocytes\u003C/strong\u003E are elongated red blood cells seen in hereditary elliptocytosis, a genetic condition, and are not associated with vitamin B12 deficiency.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vitamin B12 (cobalamin) deficiency is a common cause of macrocytic anaemia.","Patients who undergo gastric bypass surgeries have an increased risk of vitamin B12 deficiency.","Hyper-segmented neutrophils are a characteristic finding in vitamin B12 deficiency."],"references":["Stabler SP. Clinical practice. Vitamin B12 deficiency. N Engl J Med. 2013;368(2):149-160. doi:10.1056/NEJMcp1113996","Doust J. Diagnostic and management strategies for anaemia in adults. Aust Fam Physician. 2003;32(11):889-894.Ankar A, Kumar A. Vitamin B12 Deficiency. [Updated 2024 Sep 10]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK441923/","UpToDate, 2020. \u2018Clinical symptoms of selected vitamin deficiencies\u2019 in UpToDate, Graphic 63827 Version 12.0, accessed 13/4/20."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41917"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14504"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41917","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41917"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-20T08:31:14+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-20T08:36:51+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7199"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56369"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"13","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/13"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\ude78","name":"Haematology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position